<h2 id="7"><strong>7. Recover Abandoned Carts without Being Salesy (Tuft &amp; Needle)</strong></h2>



<p>If youâ€™re an e-commerce marketer, reducing cart abandonment is likely one of your primary goals.<br></p>



<p>And, chances are, youâ€™re combining <a href="https://sleeknote.com/blog/cart-abandonment-popup-examples" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">timely popups</a> with <a href="https://sleeknote.com/blog/abandoned-cart-emails" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">email marketing</a> to combat cart abandonment.<br></p>



<p>If so, you know that itâ€™s hard to convince users to complete their purchases without sounding too salesy.<br></p>



<p><a href="http://tuftandneedle.com" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">Tuft &amp; Needle</a> has the solution for you: <em>A three-part abandoned cart email flow.</em><br></p>



<p>Letâ€™s look at each.<br></p>



<p>When I left my cart on the Tuft &amp; Needle website, first, I got an email with this subject line:<br></p>



<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img width="915" height="244" src="https://sleeknote.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Subject-Line-1.png" alt="Tuft _ Needle Subject Line 1" class="wp-image-82207" srcset="https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Subject-Line-1.png 915w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Subject-Line-1-300x80.png 300w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Subject-Line-1-768x205.png 768w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Subject-Line-1-380x101.png 380w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Subject-Line-1-600x160.png 600w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Subject-Line-1-760x203.png 760w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Subject-Line-1-131x35.png 131w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Subject-Line-1-188x50.png 188w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Subject-Line-1-740x197.png 740w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Subject-Line-1-220x59.png 220w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Subject-Line-1-385x103.png 385w" sizes="(max-width: 915px) 100vw, 915px" /></figure></div>



<p>Who doesnâ€™t like a good story, right?<br></p>



<p>Honestly, I didnâ€™t think this was a promotional email until I opened to see this:<br></p>



<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img width="492" height="1024" src="https://sleeknote.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Abandoned-Cart-Email-1-492x1024.png" alt="Tuft _ Needle Abandoned Cart Email 1" class="wp-image-82187" srcset="https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Abandoned-Cart-Email-1-492x1024.png 492w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Abandoned-Cart-Email-1-144x300.png 144w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Abandoned-Cart-Email-1-380x791.png 380w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Abandoned-Cart-Email-1-600x1248.png 600w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Abandoned-Cart-Email-1-17x35.png 17w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Abandoned-Cart-Email-1-24x50.png 24w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Abandoned-Cart-Email-1-235x490.png 235w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Abandoned-Cart-Email-1-220x458.png 220w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Abandoned-Cart-Email-1-385x801.png 385w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Tuft-_-Needle-Abandoned-Cart-Email-1.png 632w" sizes="(max-width: 492px) 100vw, 492px" /></figure></div>



<p>In the first part of their cart abandonment flow, Tuft &amp; Needle joins the conversation in your head by acknowledging that <em>mattress shopping sucks. </em>(Yes, this is coming from a mattress brand.)<br></p>



<p>After positioning themselves as the frontrunners of mattress e-tailers, they ask the questions that are likely in your head: <em>How do you make the right choice?</em><br></p>



<p>Next, they create <a href="https://sleeknote.com/blog/social-proof" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">social proof</a> by comparing you to their one million customers.<br></p>



<p>In the middle of the email, you see a warning with a hyperlink on it: <strong>Donâ€™t buy a mattress without reading this first.</strong><br></p>



<p>When you click the link, youâ€™re sent to <a href="http://www.tuftandneedle.com/lp/12-reasons/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">this landing page</a> where the company further handles your possible objections:<br></p>



