<p>Overall, this is a brilliant email flow to convert abandoned carts. Whatâ€™s better, you can easily replicate Tuft &amp; Needleâ€™s <a href="https://sleeknote.com/blog/persuasive-copywriting-techniques" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">persuasive copywriting</a> by following these three steps:<br></p>



<ul><li>Handle possible objections in prospectsâ€™ minds;</li><li>Show how <em>different </em>you are than your competitors; and</li><li>Ease prospectsâ€™ minds with your satisfaction guarantee.</li></ul>



<h2 id="8"><strong>8. Re-Engage Inactive Prospects (Beardbrand)</strong></h2>



<p>Most marketers spend valuable hours (and resources) to grow their email lists.<br></p>



<p>Yet, a dormant email list with little to no engagement means nothing for your business.<br></p>



<p>Knowing this well, <a href="https://sleeknote.com/blog/beardbrand-marketing" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">Beardbrand</a> finds a creative way to <a href="https://sleeknote.com/blog/re-engage-inactive-subscribers" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">re-engage their inactive subscribers</a> and get back on top of prospectsâ€™ minds.<br></p>



<p>Itâ€™s been a few months since I last visited the companyâ€™s website, until one day I saw this email in my inbox:<br></p>



<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img width="791" height="296" src="https://sleeknote.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Subject-Line.png" alt="Beardbrand Subject Line" class="wp-image-82087" srcset="https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Subject-Line.png 791w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Subject-Line-300x112.png 300w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Subject-Line-768x287.png 768w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Subject-Line-380x142.png 380w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Subject-Line-600x225.png 600w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Subject-Line-760x284.png 760w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Subject-Line-94x35.png 94w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Subject-Line-134x50.png 134w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Subject-Line-740x277.png 740w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Subject-Line-220x82.png 220w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Subject-Line-385x144.png 385w" sizes="(max-width: 791px) 100vw, 791px" /></figure></div>



<p>In full honesty, Iâ€™m not in Beardbrandâ€™s target audience, and my relationship with them is simply marketing-related. Even so, this subject line piqued my interest, and I opened the email to see this:<br></p>



<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img width="537" height="985" src="https://sleeknote.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-1.png" alt="Beardbrand Email 1" class="wp-image-82079" srcset="https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-1.png 537w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-1-164x300.png 164w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-1-380x697.png 380w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-1-19x35.png 19w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-1-27x50.png 27w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-1-267x490.png 267w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-1-220x404.png 220w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-1-385x706.png 385w" sizes="(max-width: 537px) 100vw, 537px" /></figure></div>



<p>Sent by the companyâ€™s founder, Eric Bandholz, this re-engagement email is built on a simple fact: <em>Human hair grows about 0.5 inches a month.</em><br></p>



<p>Instead of writing that I havenâ€™t visited their website in three months, the company cleverly uses this trivia by saying, â€œYour beard grew 1.5â€³ since your last visit.â€<br></p>



<p>After stating a simple fact about my browsing behavior without guilt-tripping, Beardbrand changes the subject to their products with a smart twist:<br></p>



<p><em>While you canâ€™t make your hair grow faster, you can make it healthier.</em><br></p>



<p>Unsurprisingly, the key to healthy facial hair is Beardbrandâ€™s products.<br></p>



<p>After catching your interest with this smooth, engaging introduction, they conclude the email with product recommendations:<br></p>



<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img width="675" height="959" src="https://sleeknote.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-2.png" alt="Beardbrand Email 2" class="wp-image-82083" srcset="https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-2.png 675w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-2-211x300.png 211w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-2-380x540.png 380w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-2-600x852.png 600w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-2-25x35.png 25w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-2-35x50.png 35w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-2-345x490.png 345w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-2-220x313.png 220w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Email-2-385x547.png 385w" sizes="(max-width: 675px) 100vw, 675px" /></figure></div>



<p>However, rather than write â€œRecommended Products,â€ they trigger your <a href="https://sleeknote.com/blog/fomo-marketing" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">fear-of-missing-out</a> (FOMO) with a CTA button that reads â€œCheck Out What Iâ€™ve Missed.â€<br></p>



<h2 id="9"><strong>9. Appreciate Your Subscribers (Glossier)</strong></h2>



<p>While inactive subscribers are worth your time and energy, your active subscribers are equally, if not more, important for your brand.<br></p>



<p>With the right messages and incentives, you can turn your active subscribers into brand evangelists, let alone lifelong customers.<br></p>



<p>Contrary to popular belief, you donâ€™t always need to hand out discount codes or free products to keep your subscribers happy.<br></p>



<p>Sometimes, all it takes is a heartfelt thank you note.<br></p>



<p><a href="https://www.glossier.com/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">Glossier</a> doesnâ€™t take their subscribers for granted. I know this because, recently, I got this email from them:<br></p>



<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img width="571" height="286" src="https://sleeknote.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Subject-Line.png" alt="Glossier Subject Line" class="wp-image-82167" srcset="https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Subject-Line.png 571w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Subject-Line-300x150.png 300w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Subject-Line-380x190.png 380w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Subject-Line-70x35.png 70w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Subject-Line-100x50.png 100w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Subject-Line-220x110.png 220w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Subject-Line-385x193.png 385w" sizes="(max-width: 571px) 100vw, 571px" /></figure></div>



<p>Since Iâ€™m used to receiving (almost only) promotional emails from e-commerce companies, this simple subject line stood out in my inbox, and I opened the email immediately.<br></p>



<p>To my surprise, this was the content of the email:<br></p>



<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img width="698" height="961" src="https://sleeknote.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Appreciation-Email.png" alt="Glossier Appreciation Email" class="wp-image-82163" srcset="https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Appreciation-Email.png 698w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Appreciation-Email-218x300.png 218w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Appreciation-Email-380x523.png 380w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Appreciation-Email-600x826.png 600w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Appreciation-Email-25x35.png 25w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Appreciation-Email-36x50.png 36w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Appreciation-Email-356x490.png 356w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Appreciation-Email-220x303.png 220w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Glossier-Appreciation-Email-385x530.png 385w" sizes="(max-width: 698px) 100vw, 698px" /></figure></div>



<p>Glossier doesnâ€™t have any products, announcements, or CTAs in this email. They compliment me because I often visit their website and open their emails.<br></p>



<p>But hereâ€™s the catch: All elements in this email, including the image, the button, and icons, are linked to their <a href="https://sleeknote.com/blog/product-page-examples" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">product pages</a>. Meaning, any place you click in this email takes you to browse the companyâ€™s products.<br></p>



<p>This way, Glossier subtly lures you into their product pages. But they also create a positive brand image in the eyes of their active subscribers.<br></p>


